> **Kogod 118**

## Course Description

This course introduces important database concepts, including data modeling, database design, data extraction and data analysis skills needed to transform raw data into useful business information and knowledge for decision making and problem solving. Includes relational design, big data challenges, big data analytics and tools, data warehousing, data querying and reporting.

## Learning Outcomes

1. Describe, define and apply the major components of the relational database model to database design;

2. Utilize relational database modeling techniques for defining a single entity class, a one to one (1:1) relationship between entity classes, a one to many (1:M) relationship between entity classes, a many to many (M:M) relationship between entity classes

3. Be able to understand and apply Normalization and Functional Dependencies to design, create and utilize a relational database

4. Learn and apply the Structured Query Language (SQL) for database definition and manipulation;

5. Become familiar with the 3Vs of Big Data: volume, velocity, variety,

6. Understand the fundamental concepts of Big Data management, analysis and technologies as applied to AI, data analytics and other big data needs.

7. Understand the concepts of Vector databases and how they are used in AI and machine learning

8. Translate real-world questions or intellectual inquiries into quantitative frameworks. 

9. Select and apply appropriate quantitative methods or reasoning. 

10. Draw appropriate insights from the application of a quantitative framework. 

11. Explain quantitative reasoning and insights using appropriate forms of representation so that others could replicate the findings. 


## Required Textbook & Course Material

**Required:** Modern Database Management (10th, 11th, 12th or 13th Editions), Jeffrey A. Hoffer Mary Prescott, Heikki Topi. Publisher: Addison-Wesley. ISBN: 0136088392 (10th Edition)

Note: Any edition of the Modern Database Management book is acceptable for this class as the reading are exactly the same material. I have included the specific pages for each edition in the weekly syllabus below.

**Required:** The student should have access to a Relational database such as or Microsoft Access on MySQL, to practice some of the assignments.

### Workshop/Homework Assignments

There will be a number of in-class workshops and take-home homework assignments that each student needs to complete. The purpose of the homework assignments (and their preceding workshop exercises) is to give students hands-on experience (both with class and outside class) with data and database development and implementation methods so that students can complete their projects successfully.

### In Class Workshops

Workshops provide an opportunity to practice hands-on and learn to apply the lecture topics. Workshops will be an integral part of the class sessions. Typically, I will introduce and lecture on a database topic and then you apply and practice the application of that topic with professor feedback.

### Homework Assignments

Homework problems will be collected and graded. You are responsible for solving these problems. Homework problems are individual work only. You are not to share your solutions with other students

### Research Paper on Advanced Database or Big Data topic

A paper on advanced Database or Big Data topic is required for individuals taking this class. The students may select from a wide variety of topics in the Database or Big Data areas. The paper could a survey paper on how a specific data approach is applied in a specific industry or global region. The paper could also be on a more technical or method specific topic. I suggest that you pick a topic in the field of Database or Big Data that you are very interested in and utilize the paper to increase your knowledge.

As needed, the Professor will meet with each Graduate student individually throughout the semester to discuss and review the student's topic selection and their progress on the paper.

A short abstract on the topic of the paper should be submitted to the professor by **TBD**. The final paper should be approximately 10 pages, double-spaced including figures and references and will be due on the last day of classes: **TBD**

